now we move to version 3: automated certificate rotation with alerting. This is production-grade, so you never lose access to your cluster. I’ll break it down carefully for a beginner, line by line.

Goal

We want a system that:

Detects certificates that are about to expire (for users you onboarded).
Automatically generates a new key + CSR, gets it approved, and updates the user’s kubeconfig.
Sends an alert if something goes wrong.
Keeps backups of old and new certs.

Think of it like auto-renewal for Kubernetes access.

Step 0 — Directory Layout

mkdir -p ~/k8s-users/certs
mkdir -p ~/k8s-users/kubeconfigs
mkdir -p ~/k8s-users/logs

Explanation:

certs/ → keys + certificates
kubeconfigs/ → per-user kubeconfig files
logs/ → track rotations and errors

Step 1 — Rotation Script

Save this as rotate-k8s-certs.sh:
#!/bin/bash
# Usage: ./rotate-k8s-certs.sh <username> <group> <namespace> <alert-email>

USERNAME=$1
GROUP=$2
NAMESPACE=$3
ALERT_EMAIL=$4

if [ -z "$USERNAME" ] || [ -z "$GROUP" ] || [ -z "$NAMESPACE" ] || [ -z "$ALERT_EMAIL" ]; then
  echo "Usage: $0 <username> <group> <namespace> <alert-email>"
  exit 1
fi

CERT_DIR=certs/$USERNAME
KUBECONFIG_FILE=kubeconfigs/${USERNAME}-kubeconfig
LOG_FILE=logs/${USERNAME}-rotation.log

mkdir -p $CERT_DIR
touch $LOG_FILE

# Step 1️⃣: Check expiration
if [ -f $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt ]; then
  EXPIRATION_DATE=$(openssl x509 -enddate -noout -in $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt | cut -d= -f2)
  EXPIRATION_SEC=$(date -d "$EXPIRATION_DATE" +%s)
  NOW_SEC=$(date +%s)
  DIFF=$(( EXPIRATION_SEC - NOW_SEC ))

  # If less than 3 days, rotate
  if [ $DIFF -le 259200 ]; then
    echo "$(date): Certificate is expiring soon, rotating..." >> $LOG_FILE
  else
    echo "$(date): Certificate still valid, skipping rotation." >> $LOG_FILE
    exit 0
  fi
else
  echo "$(date): No certificate found, generating new one..." >> $LOG_FILE
fi

# Step 2️⃣: Backup existing certs
if [ -f $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt ] || [ -f $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key ]; then
  tar czf $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-backup-$(date +%F).tgz $CERT_DIR
  echo "$(date): Backup created" >> $LOG_FILE
fi

# Step 3️⃣: Generate new key and CSR
openssl genrsa -out $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key 2048
openssl req -new -key $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key -out $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr -subj "/CN=${USERNAME}/O=${GROUP}"
CSR_BASE64=$(cat $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr | base64 | tr -d '\n')

# Step 4️⃣: Apply Kubernetes CSR
cat <<EOF > $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: ${USERNAME}-csr
spec:
  request: ${CSR_BASE64}
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  expirationSeconds: 86400
  usages:
    - client auth
EOF

kubectl apply -f $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
kubectl certificate approve ${USERNAME}-csr
kubectl get csr ${USERNAME}-csr -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' | base64 -d > $CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt

echo "$(date): Certificate rotation complete" >> $LOG_FILE

# Step 5️⃣: Update kubeconfig
kubectl config set-credentials $USERNAME \
  --client-certificate=$CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt \
  --client-key=$CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key \
  --embed-certs=true \
  --kubeconfig=$KUBECONFIG_FILE

kubectl config set-context ${USERNAME}-context \
  --cluster=$(kubectl config view -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].name}') \
  --user=$USERNAME \
  --namespace=$NAMESPACE \
  --kubeconfig=$KUBECONFIG_FILE

kubectl config use-context ${USERNAME}-context --kubeconfig=$KUBECONFIG_FILE

echo "$(date): Kubeconfig updated" >> $LOG_FILE

# Step 6️⃣: Alert if log has errors
if grep -i "error" $LOG_FILE; then
  echo "Certificate rotation failed for $USERNAME. Check log: $LOG_FILE" | mail -s "K8s Cert Rotation Failed" $ALERT_EMAIL
fi

Step 2 — How it Works

| Step | Explanation (Beginner)                                                       |
| ---- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1    | Checks if the existing cert is **expiring in 3 days**. If not, skip rotation |
| 2    | Backs up old key + cert just in case                                         |
| 3    | Generates a **new key + CSR**                                                |
| 4    | Applies and approves CSR in Kubernetes                                       |
| 5    | Extracts the signed certificate and updates **per-user kubeconfig**          |
| 6    | Checks the log for errors; sends an **email alert** if something failed      |

Step 3 — Schedule Automatic Rotation
Use cron to check daily:
crontab -e
0 2 * * * /home/youruser/k8s-users/rotate-k8s-certs.sh dahir dev-group default admin@example.com >> /home/youruser/k8s-users/logs/rotate.log 2>&1
Runs every day at 2:00 AM
Rotates certificate if expiring
Logs everything to rotate.log
Step 4 — RBAC Reminder
Even with a valid certificate:

User can’t do anything without RoleBinding
Make sure each user has proper permissions
Example:

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: dahir-binding
  namespace: default
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: dahir
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: view
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

