now we go full automation: version 4, a bulk user onboarding + rotation + reporting system for Kubernetes certificates. This is production-grade, fully hands-off. I’ll break it down carefully so even a beginner can understand every piece.
Goal of Version 4
Onboard hundreds of users at once.
Automatically generate keys, CSRs, approve certs, and create kubeconfigs.
Rotate certificates before they expire.
Send dashboard-style email reports of rotation status.
Keep backups for every user automatically.

Think of it like Kubernetes PKI as a service.

Step 0 — CSV Input for Users

Create a CSV users.csv:
username,group,namespace,email
dahir,dev-group,default,admin@example.com
alice,dev-group,default,admin@example.com
bob,qa-group,testing,admin@example.com
Step 1 — Bulk Automation Script

Save as bulk-k8s-user-manager.sh:
#!/bin/bash
# Usage: ./bulk-k8s-user-manager.sh users.csv

CSV_FILE=$1
if [ -z "$CSV_FILE" ]; then
  echo "Usage: $0 users.csv"
  exit 1
fi

CERT_DIR=certs
KUBECONFIG_DIR=kubeconfigs
LOG_DIR=logs
mkdir -p $CERT_DIR $KUBECONFIG_DIR $LOG_DIR

REPORT="$LOG_DIR/bulk-report-$(date +%F).txt"
echo "Kubernetes Bulk User Onboarding & Rotation Report - $(date)" > $REPORT
echo "------------------------------------------------------------" >> $REPORT

while IFS=',' read -r USERNAME GROUP NAMESPACE ALERT_EMAIL; do
  if [ "$USERNAME" = "username" ]; then
    continue  # Skip header
  fi

  echo "Processing user: $USERNAME" >> $REPORT

  USER_CERT_DIR=$CERT_DIR/$USERNAME
  USER_KUBECONFIG=$KUBECONFIG_DIR/${USERNAME}-kubeconfig
  mkdir -p $USER_CERT_DIR

  # Check if cert exists
  ROTATE=false
  if [ -f $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt ]; then
    EXP_DATE=$(openssl x509 -enddate -noout -in $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt | cut -d= -f2)
    EXP_SEC=$(date -d "$EXP_DATE" +%s)
    NOW_SEC=$(date +%s)
    DIFF=$(( EXP_SEC - NOW_SEC ))
    if [ $DIFF -le 259200 ]; then
      ROTATE=true
      echo "$(date): Certificate expiring soon, rotating..." >> $REPORT
    fi
  else
    ROTATE=true
    echo "$(date): No certificate found, generating new one..." >> $REPORT
  fi

  if [ "$ROTATE" = true ]; then
    # Backup old certs
    if [ -f $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt ] || [ -f $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key ]; then
      tar czf $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-backup-$(date +%F).tgz $USER_CERT_DIR
      echo "$(date): Backup created" >> $REPORT
    fi

    # Generate key & CSR
    openssl genrsa -out $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key 2048
    openssl req -new -key $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key -out $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr -subj "/CN=${USERNAME}/O=${GROUP}"
    CSR_BASE64=$(cat $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.csr | base64 | tr -d '\n')

    # Apply CSR
    cat <<EOF > $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
apiVersion: certificates.k8s.io/v1
kind: CertificateSigningRequest
metadata:
  name: ${USERNAME}-csr
spec:
  request: ${CSR_BASE64}
  signerName: kubernetes.io/kube-apiserver-client
  expirationSeconds: 86400
  usages:
    - client auth
EOF

    kubectl apply -f $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}-csr.yaml
    kubectl certificate approve ${USERNAME}-csr
    kubectl get csr ${USERNAME}-csr -o jsonpath='{.status.certificate}' | base64 -d > $USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt
    echo "$(date): Certificate generated/rotated" >> $REPORT

    # Update kubeconfig
    kubectl config set-cluster default-cluster \
      --server=$(kubectl config view -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.server}') \
      --certificate-authority=$(kubectl config view -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.certificate-authority}') \
      --embed-certs=true \
      --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

    kubectl config set-credentials $USERNAME \
      --client-certificate=$USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.crt \
      --client-key=$USER_CERT_DIR/${USERNAME}.key \
      --embed-certs=true \
      --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

    kubectl config set-context ${USERNAME}-context \
      --cluster=default-cluster \
      --user=$USERNAME \
      --namespace=$NAMESPACE \
      --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG

    kubectl config use-context ${USERNAME}-context --kubeconfig=$USER_KUBECONFIG
    echo "$(date): Kubeconfig updated" >> $REPORT
  else
    echo "$(date): Certificate still valid, skipping rotation." >> $REPORT
  fi

done < $CSV_FILE

# Step 2️⃣: Send report via email
if command -v mail &> /dev/null; then
  cat $REPORT | mail -s "K8s Bulk User Report - $(date)" $(awk -F, 'NR>1 {print $4}' $CSV_FILE | sort | uniq | tr '\n' ',')
fi

echo "Bulk operation complete. Report: $REPORT"
Step 2 — How Version 4 Works
CSV Input → reads users, groups, namespaces, and emails.
Check certificate expiration → rotate if ≤3 days or missing.
Backup old certs → keeps safe copies.
Generate key + CSR → per user.
Apply CSR and approve → signed by Kubernetes automatically.
Update kubeconfig → each user has an isolated kubeconfig file.
Dashboard email report → shows which certs rotated, which skipped.
Logs everything → can review later if something goes wrong.

Step 3 — Automate with Cron

crontab -e
0 2 * * * /home/youruser/k8s-users/bulk-k8s-user-manager.sh /home/youruser/k8s-users/users.csv >> /home/youruser/k8s-users/logs/bulk.log 2>&1
Automatically checks all users in users.csv
Rotates certs that are expiring
Emails report to admins
